    </div>
    <p class="pf-note">Your birth-year element is revealed only when you enter a date. The element above is the animal's symbolic element.</p>
  </header>

  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">The crossing</p>
    <h2>Where Aries and Dragon meet</h2>
    <p>You arrive with force and a clear direction, and you would rather act and adjust than wait and wonder. You take up space without meaning to, and people either fall in behind you or brace against you. You protect scale, momentum, and the right to decide. You mistake stillness for weakness in yourself long before you mistake it in anyone else.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">Gifts</p>
    <h2>What this animal does well</h2>
    <ul class="pf-list"><li>You start things that would intimidate almost anyone else.</li><li>You make decisions under pressure while others are still gathering nerve.</li><li>You give people who are lost a direction to move in.</li></ul>
  </section>

  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">Shadow form</p>
    <h2>How it distorts under pressure</h2>
    <p>Your strength distorts into domination. When you feel unsteady you get louder and more certain, not quieter, and you flatten the room to feel solid again. You confuse being obeyed with being right, and you can leave a trail of people who agreed with you only to end the pressure.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">Awakened form</p>
    <h2>The same strength, integrated</h2>
    <p>The awakened T-Rex keeps the force and aims it. You learn that restraint is a form of power, not a loss of it, and that the strongest move in a room is often to hold still and let someone smaller finish speaking. Your certainty becomes something people trust instead of something they endure.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">The five gates</p>
    <h2>A reading in five doors</h2>
    <div class="pf-gates">
      <article class="pf-gate"><span class="lab">Gate of Ground</span><h3>Where you stand now</h3><p>You are moving fast and feeling little, because feeling was never on the schedule.</p></article>
      <article class="pf-gate"><span class="lab">Gate of Hunger</span><h3>What is asking for attention</h3><p>To be trusted rather than obeyed, which asks you to slow down enough to be questioned.</p></article>
      <article class="pf-gate"><span class="lab">Gate of Season</span><h3>What to build next</h3><p>Pick one decision this month and deliberately do not make it alone. Bring one person in before you move.</p></article>
      <article class="pf-gate"><span class="lab">Gate of Shadow</span><h3>What could quietly distort your path</h3><p>Getting louder when you feel unsteady. The tell is that you are winning the room and losing the person.</p></article>
      <article class="pf-gate"><span class="lab">Gate of Form</span><h3>The person you become when integrated</h3><p>The one whose certainty steadies a room instead of flattening it. The practice: in one hard moment, hold still and let someone else finish.</p></article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">The Habitat</p>
    <h2>Living with your animal</h2>
    <p>A Fire nature that needs a Water counterweight. [Traditional] Fire is fed by Wood and cooled by Water; unchecked Fire scorches the room. [Primal] For the T-Rex, add one clear cooling cue to a warm, forward space so drive has a brake it can see.</p>
    <div class="pf-grid2">
      <div class="pf-card"><h3>Sanctuary zone</h3><p>A visible planning wall where scale and direction live, balanced by one quiet corner with nothing to conquer.</p></div>
      <div class="pf-card"><h3>Materials and form</h3><p>Iron, hardwood, and stone; heavy forms that hold their place. Rising and angular; a form that leads with its front edge.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pf-card" style="margin-top:16px"><h3>Colors</h3><ul class="pf-list">
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Anchor:</strong> Ember red <small style="color:var(--muted)">(a deep, steady heat, #a5301f)</small></li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Supporting:</strong> Bronze <small style="color:var(--muted)">(a grounded metallic warmth, #8a6a3a)</small></li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Activating:</strong> Bright gold <small style="color:var(--muted)">(a signal of authority used with care, #d8a83a)</small></li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Use sparingly:</strong> Cold slate <small style="color:var(--muted)">(a cooling neutral used to temper the heat, #48545e)</small></li>
    </ul></div>
    <div class="pf-card" style="margin-top:16px"><h3>Room by room</h3><ul class="pf-list">
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Bedroom.</strong> One cooling cue, soft light, no work in view. A room that lets the engine idle.</li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Work area.</strong> A planning wall you can stand in front of, plus a chair angled so others can face you as equals.</li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Entry.</strong> A pause point: something that asks you to set the momentum down for a breath.</li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Living area.</strong> A shared table where you sit, not stand, so the space reads as level.</li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Reflection space.</strong> A south-facing seat with a cool object to hold while you slow the pace.</li>
    </ul></div>
    <div class="pf-card" style="margin-top:16px"><h3>Reduce or remove</h3><ul class="pf-list"><li>Overstimulation and too many bright signals, which push an already forward nature into overdrive.</li><li>Trophies with nothing restful beside them, which keep the room in a posture of winning.</li><li>Harsh lighting, which sharpens urgency.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="pf-card" style="margin-top:16px"><h3>Seven-minute reset</h3><p>Open a window &middot; Clear the loudest surface &middot; Place one cool, heavy object &middot; Face south &middot; Take three slow breaths &middot; Write one thing you will not decide alone &middot; Sit for one minute before you move</p></div>
    <p class="pf-note">Feng Shui elements here are symbolic. They support intention and act as visual reminders. They are not claims that any object, color, or direction produces wealth, health, romance, or success.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">Keeper Stones</p>
    <h2>Symbolic materials for this animal</h2>
    <div class="pf-stones">
      <div class="pf-stone"><span class="role">Anchor</span><span class="nm">Red jasper</span><span class="why">A grounding stone for steady strength rather than restless heat.</span><span class="care">Care: Durable; rinse and dry.</span></div>
      <div class="pf-stone"><span class="role">Clarity</span><span class="nm">Hematite</span><span class="why">A cooling, weighty stone for taking the temperature down before deciding.</span><span class="care">Care: Keep dry to avoid surface rust.</span></div>
      <div class="pf-stone"><span class="role">Courage</span><span class="nm">Tiger's eye</span><span class="why">For the courage to lead without needing to dominate.</span><span class="care">Care: Safe to handle.</span></div>
      <div class="pf-stone"><span class="role">Boundary</span><span class="nm">Obsidian</span><span class="why">A mirror stone for seeing your own force before it lands on someone.</span><span class="care">Care: Edges can be sharp; handle gently.</span></div>
      <div class="pf-stone"><span class="role">Moon</span><span class="nm">Aquamarine</span><span class="why">A watery moon stone to soften a fire nature at rest.</span><span class="care">Care: Can fade in strong sun.</span></div>
    </div>
    <p class="pf-note">Stones are cultural and symbolic tools, not medical treatment. Some are unsafe in water or fade in sunlight; a few can be brittle around children or pets. Follow the care note for each.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">Moon rhythm</p>
    <h2>Working with the phases</h2>
    <ul class="pf-list">
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">New moon.</strong> Name one thing you will build with people, not over them.</li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Waxing moon.</strong> Move on it, and invite one voice you would normally overrule.</li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Full moon.</strong> Take stock of what your drive built, and who helped, out loud.</li>
      <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Waning moon.</strong> Put down one fight you were only winning to feel solid.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  
  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">Direction</p>
    <h2>Where to face</h2>
    <div class="pf-grid2">
      <div class="pf-card"><h3>Your directions</h3><ul class="pf-list">
        <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Primary.</strong> South</li>
        <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Supporting.</strong> East</li>
        <li><strong style="color:var(--moon)">Recovery.</strong> North</li>
      </ul></div>
      <div class="pf-card"><h3>How to use it</h3><p>South carries visibility and heat. Face it when you want to be seen or to begin something bold, and retreat toward the quiet North to cool a nature that runs hot.</p></div>
    </div>
    <p class="pf-note">A direction is a reflective cue, not a rule. Adapt it when a room cannot follow it.</p>
  </section>
  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">Nourishment</p>
    <h2>How this animal eats well</h2>
    <p>Your guiding flavor is <strong style="color:var(--moon)">bitter and bright</strong>, leaning cooling. This suits leafy greens, citrus, bitter roots, and foods that cool a fast engine. A gentle counterweight is heavy heating plates when you are already wound tight.</p>
    <div class="pf-card"><h3>The table ritual</h3><p>One seated course, eaten slowly, before you rush to the next thing. <span class="pf-note" style="display:block;margin-top:8px">Strongest in high summer.</span></p></div>
    <p class="pf-note">This is symbolic and cultural, not nutrition or medical advice. No food heals or guarantees anything, and this is never a diet.</p>
  </section>
  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">Moon for you</p>
    <h2>The phase that serves you</h2>
    <p>Your fire burns brightest at the full moon. Spend it in the open, then let the waning crescent cool you down before you start again.</p>
    <div class="pf-links">
      <a href="/moon/phases/full-moon/">Power phase: Full Moon</a>
      <a href="/moon/phases/waning-crescent/">Rest phase: Waning Crescent</a>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="pf-section">
    <p class="pf-eyebrow">Best days</p>
    <h2>Favorable days ahead</h2>
    <p>In the Chinese tradition each day carries its own animal. Days ruled by the Dragon's allies tend to favor connection and fresh starts; days ruled by its opposite ask for a little patience.</p>
    <ul class="pf-list" id="pf-bestdays"><li class="pf-note">Reading the calendar…</li></ul>
    <p class="pf-note">Symbolic timing for reflection, not a promise about any day. <a href="/best-days.html">See your full calendar of best days.</a></p>
  </section>
